      "lesson title": "Who Is Responsible for AI Decisions in Public Services?",
      "order": 1,
      "Description": "When artificial intelligence is used to make decisions in public services, such as allocating benefits, triaging healthcare, or flagging individuals for investigation, it is not always clear who should be held accountable when something goes wrong. This lesson explores the shared and sometimes competing responsibilities of the technology vendors who build AI systems, the public agencies that deploy them, and the policymakers who set the rules governing their use. We will look at real-world examples to understand how accountability can become fragmented, leaving citizens without clear routes to challenge decisions that affect their lives. By the end of this lesson, you will be able to identify the key parties involved in AI decision-making in public services and understand the basic principles that should guide accountability. No prior technical knowledge is required, and the focus throughout is on practical understanding rather than complex theory.",
